<center>
<h1>About me</h1>
</center>
<main>
<hr>


I am an applied algebraic topologist. I am interested in both developing the theoretical tools of topological data analysis and applying these tools to real-world data, with a particular view towards theoretical neuroscience. I am currently an Independent Fellow at the <a href="https://www.rockefeller.edu/research/interdisciplinary-centers/center-studies-physics-biology/">Center for Studies in Physics and Biology</a> at the Rockefeller University. Prevsiouy, I worked with <a href="http://www.chadgiusti.com/">Chad Giusti</a> as a postdoc at the <a href="https://www.mathsci.udel.edu/">University of Delaware</a> in the Department of Mathematical Sciences. Before that, I studied  theoretical mathematics at (The) Ohio State University, where I earned my PhD under <a href="https://people.math.osu.edu/harper.903/">John E. Harper</a> in homotopy theory. Here is a copy of my <a href="2024_teaching_CV.pdf">CV</a> (last updated September 2024).

<br><br>

In addition to my research, I very much enjoy teaching. I have served as an instructor both at the University of Delaware and as a graduate student at Ohio State, where I also served as a TA for a wide variety of courses. My teaching has been recognized both at the departmental and university level. Most recently, I was independently nominated for the University of Delaware's Excellence in Teaching Award. As a graduate student in 2020, I received the Graduate Associate Teaching Award, Ohio State’s highest recognition of teaching excellence by graduate students. For more information, please see my teaching section below.










