<center>
<a class="anchor" name="Research"></a>
<h1>Research</h1>
</center>
<hr>

My research is in applied algebraic topology and uses topological tools to analyze and compare high-dimensional data sets. In further detail, my work focuses on 1) reducing the dimensionality of large data sets in topologically-invariant ways, 2) using tools from topological data analysis to study the geometry of neural representations and neural circuits, using both real-world and simulated data, and 3) developing novel theoretical approaches to modern applied problems using advanced tools from algebraic topology and homotopy theory. 

<br><br>

My PhD research was in homotopy theory and studied spectra with additional algebraic structure described by an operad. I used tools from category theory, functor calculus, and chromatic homotopy theory to prove a number of results identifying conditions under which complex algebraic structure can be recovered by "gluing together" simpler approximations. A brief summary of this work, made for the <a href="https://s.wayne.edu/echt/electronic-algebraic-topology-employment-network/">eATEN</a>, can be found <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Va8fOPadRn4"> here.</a><br><br>



<center><u>
<h3> Publications/preprints 
</h3> 
</u></center>

<b> O(k)-equivariant dimensionality reduction on Stiefel manifolds </b>
<br>
(with A. Lee, H. Lee, J. Perea, M. Weinstein).
<br>
Many real-world data sets live on high-dimensional Stiefel manifolds and benefit from projections onto lower-dimensional Stiefel manifolds. We describe an algorithm, called <i>Principal Stiefel Coordinates</i>, that accomplishes this, and does so in an equivariant way. Hence, our algorithm extends to data living on Grassmannian manifolds as well. We perform multiple numerical experiments on real-world and synthetic data sets. Preprint available through <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.10775">arXiv</a>.
<br>
<br>

<b> Spherical coordinates from persistent cohomology </b> (with S. Schonsheck).
<br>
<i> Journal of Applied and Computational Topology, <b> 8 </b>, 149-173, 2024. </i>
<br>
We describe a method to obtain spherical parameterizations of arbitrary data through the use of persistent cohomology and variational optimization. This builds on the "circular coordinates" of de Silva--Morozov--Vejdemo-Johansson and Perea, answering in the affirmative a question first posed by de Silva et al. in 2011. (22 pages). Also available through <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2209.02791">arXiv</a>.

<br>
<br>

<b> Toroidal coordinates: decorrelating circular coordinates with lattice reduction </b> (with J. Bush, H. Gakhar, J. Perea, T. Rask, L. Scoccola, L. Zhou).
<br>
<i>39th International Symposium on Computational Geometry (SoCG 2023)</i>, <b>258</b>, 57:1-57:20 (2023). 
<br>
The circular coordinates algorithm of de Silva, Morozov, and Vejdemo-Johansson takes as input a dataset together with a cohomology class representing a 1-dimensional hole in the data; the output is a map from the data into the circle that captures this geometric feature and that is of minimal energy in a suitable sense. However, when applied to several cohomology classes, the output circle-valued maps can be “geometrically correlated” even if the chosen cohomology classes are linearly independent. We describe a systematic procedure for constructing low energy torus-valued maps on data, and showcase our procedure with computational examples. (20 pages). Also available through <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.07201">arXiv</a>.

<br>
<br>

<b> On the chromatic localization of the homotopy completion tower for O-algebras</b> (with C. Ogle).
<br>
<i> New York Journal of Mathematics, <b> 28 </b>, 1042-1056, 2022. </i>
<br>
The completion tower of a nonunital commutative ring is a classical construction in commutative algebra. In the setting of structured ring spectra as modeled by algebras over a spectral operad, the analogous construction is the homotopy completion tower. The purpose of this brief note is to show that localization with respect to the Johnson-Wilson spectrum E(n) commutes with the terms of this tower. (15 pages) <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2012.10539">arXiv</a> / <a href="https://people.math.osu.edu/schonsheck.2/research_files/E_n_localization.pdf">pdf</a>


<br>
<br>

<b> TQ-completion and the Taylor tower of the identity functor.</b>
<br>
<i>Journal of Homotopy and Related Structures</i> 
<b> 17</b> (2) 201-216, 2022. 
<br>
This paper studies the convergence of the Taylor tower of the identity functor in the context of operadic algebras in spectra. Specifically, we show that if a A is a (-1)-connected O-algebra with 0-connected TQ-homology spectrum, then there is a natural weak equivalence between the limit of the Taylor tower of the identity functor evaluated on A and the TQ-completion of A. Since, in this context, the identity functor is only known to be 0-analytic, this result extends knowledge of the Taylor tower of the identity beyond its "radius of convergence." (14 pages), 2022. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2011.00570">arXiv</a> / <a href="https://people.math.osu.edu/schonsheck.2/research_files/Taylor_tower_of_identity.pdf">pdf</a>

<br>
<br>

<b> Fibration theorems for TQ-completion of structured ring spectra. </b>
<br>
<i> Tbilisi Math. Journal: Special Issue on Homotopy Theory, Spectra, and Structured Ring Spectra</i>, 2020.
<br>

Working in the context of algebras over a spectral operad, we prove that completion with respect to topological Quillen homology preserves homotopy fibration sequences in which the base and total objects are connected. More generally, we show that similar results remain true if we replace "homotopy fibration sequence" with "homotopy pullback square." (14 pages) <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2002.00038">arXiv</a> / <a href="https://people.math.osu.edu/schonsheck.2/research_files/Fibration_theorems.pdf">pdf</a>

<br>
<br>

<b> On the cop number of generalized Petersen graphs. </b> 

 <br>
(With T. Ball, R. Bell, J. Guzman, and M. Hanson-Colvin). <i>Discrete Mathematics</i> <b>340</b> (6) 1381-1388, 2017.<br>
This paper came about from work done during the SURIEM program (an REU) at Michigan State University in 2014. <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012365X16303387/">journal</a> / <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1509.04696">arXiv</a>

<br>
<center><u>
<h3> In preparation 
</h3> 
</u></center>


<b> Relative neural population size modulates learnability of cyclic features of neural code</b><br>
(with C. Giusti).
<br>
We study the propagation of cyclic features of neural code through feedforward rate-model networks. Our primary results are 1) one-layer feedforward networks with connections drawn from a random distribution biased towards inhibitory connections do not generally propagate cyclic features of neural code 2) a simple Hebbian learning rule to update network connections successfully constructs networks that do propagate cyclic features and 3) under certain biologically plausible parameter choices, the inhibition and propagation of such features can be modulated by the size of the output neuron population.
<br>
<br>


<b> A generalized Dowker Theorem</b>
<br>
(with C. Giusti, V. Itskov, M. Robinson, R. Sazdanovic, V. de Silva, M. Vaupel, H-R. Yoon).
A classical theorem of C. H. Dowker implies that, from a topological perspective, the role of "witnesses" and "landmarks" of a data set are interchangeable. We generalize this theorem to multi-way relations of sets. We offer several proofs from a variety of perspectives, and discuss the historical development of results of this nature. 
<br>
<br>
<br>


